at' b"i'm doing here. i believe that god is the source and ground of" b'being. when you say that "god does not exist", i also accept this' b'statement but we obviously mean two different things by it. however,' b'in what follows i will use the phrase "the existence of god" in it\'s' b"'usual sense' and this is the sense that i think you are using it." b'i would like a clarification upon what you mean by "the existence of' b'god".' b'' b'we also might differ upon what it means to have faith. here is what' b'webster says:' b'' b'faith' b'1a: allegiance to duty or a person: loyalty' b"b fidelity to one's promises" b'(2): sincerity of intentions' b'2a belief and trust in and loyalty to god' b'(2): belief in the traditional doctrines of a religion' b'b firm belief in something for which there is no proof' b'^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^' b'(2): complete trust' b'3: something that is believed esp. with strong conviction; esp: a system' b'^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^' b'of religious beliefs' b'syn see belief' b'' b'' b'' b'one can never prove that god does or does not exist. when you say' b'that you believe god does not exist, and that this is an opinion' b'"based upon observation", i will have to ask "what observtions are' b'you refering to?" there are no observations pro or con that' b'are valid here in establishing a positive belief. all observations' b'can only point you in a direction a direction that we might even' b'be predisposed to (by predisposed i mean, for example, people whoes' b'partents "believe in god" also tend to). to actually draw a conclusion' b'about the "existence" or "non-existence" of god requires a leap and' b'you have made this leap when you actively say "i believe that god' b'does/does not exist". personally, i think that both statements are' b'misguided. arguing over the "existence" of god is precisely the wrong way' b'to find him (and yes, i use "him" because a personal god is the only' b'viable 